@node introduction "Introduction"

@{b}1 - Introduction@{ub}

   @{b}g2h@{ub} is a little Shell/Workbench utility to convert guide
   files into html files.

   There is now a WWW site for @{b}g2h@{ub}:

   http://dept-info.labri.u-bordeaux.fr/~darnis/english/amiga
  
   then, choose option 'my softwares' and then 'g2h'.

@endnode

@node config "System requirements"

@{b}2 - System requirements@{ub}

   2.1 - Hard

   Nothing special, except an @{"Amiga" link amiga} and a monitor ;-).

   2.2 - Soft

   You need at least Kickstart 2.04 and Workbench 2.04.

@endnode

@node amiga "Amiga"

@{b}@{i}Amiga@{ub}@{ui}

   The best ever man-made machine...

@endnode

@node installation "Installation"

@{b}3 - Installation@{ub}

   Just copy the @{b}g2h@{ub} executable and its icon somewhere in you path
   (c: or tools for example). Then, copy the guide file and the html
   directory where you want.

   N.B.: if you want to use the Workbench interface of g2h, 
         you must launch @{b}g2h@{ub} by it's icon.

@endnode

@node usage "Usage"

@{b}4 - Usage@{ub}

   4.1 - From a Shell/CLI window

   You must invoke @{b}g2h@{ub} with the following syntaxe: g2h [options ...]

   Options availables:

   ?               : shows @{b}g2h@{ub}'s options.

   -v              : shows @{b}g2h@{ub}'s version number.

   -i <input file> : tells @{b}g2h@{ub} to convert the AmigaGuide file 'input file'.
                     NOTE: the -i option MUST BE THE FIRST ONE, if it's used.

   -o <path>       : sets the output directory to <path> : all html files created will go in this 
                     directory.

   -a              : add a line on the main html page below wich the fields database, copyright,
                     version and author are inserted if they were found in the original guide file.

   -w <www>        : indicates your web address, to put it at the bottom of the main page.

   -m <email>      : same as above but for your email address.

   -p <path>       : indicates the full <path> name of a picture to put on background of each html page.

   -text <RRGGBB>  : sets the text color to <RRGGBB>.

   -link <RRGGBB>  : sets the link color to <RRGGBB>.

   -vlink <RRGGBB> : sets the vlink color to <RRGGBB>.

   -alink <RRGGBB> : sets the alink color to <RRGGBB>.

   -bgcol <RRGGBB> : sets the background color to <RRGGBB>.

   -n              : no verbose: don't print anything when it works.

   4.2 - From the Workbench

   Double-clic on @{b}g2h@{ub}'s icon and fill in the string gadgets you want.
   The input file string gadget is the only one that is necessary to fill 
   in order to convert a guide file.

   Clic on the [OK] button to start the conversion, and on the [Cancel] button,
   or on the close window gadget to quit @{b}g2h@{ub}.
    
@endnode

@node work "How does it work?"

@{b}5 - How does it work?@{ub}

   0) @{b}g2h@{ub} reads the input file and creates a directory named exactly as the name of the input
      guide file. In this directory, @{b}g2h@{ub} will put all nodes of the input guide file, translated in html
      files, named exactly as the nodes names, suffixed by ".html". 
      When a link button is encountered, @{b}g2h@{ub} has for now, three alternative:

   1) The link button is a node: @{b}g2h@{ub} creates an html file named exactly as the node and puts in
      it the converted text as step 0.

   2) The link button is another file: @{b}g2h@{ub} try to read "@database" as first characters in this
      file. If it success, @{b}g2h@{ub} create a new directory named exactly as the name of the new guide
      file to convert, and converts it's nodes recursively with the same options you entered for
      the first call to @{b}g2h@{ub} as step 0. If it fails, go to step 3.

   3) If @{b}g2h@{ub} didn't read "@database" in the linked file, it deduces :) it's not a guide file.
      Then, it suppose that's an image file and make a special html file named exactly as the link
      name but suffixed with "img.html". In this file, the name of the image file is inserted as a 
      IMG SRC html tag.

      NB: I know that other file than guide files or image files are supported by AmigaGuide, but
      @{b}g2h@{ub} just do the above things...

   IMPORTANT : All files created are in lower cases and only the last 25 characters of a link are kept
   to make the file names not too long for AmigaOS. So, don't worry if some files names looks to have
   lost their begining...

@endnode

